## 4. Key Design Decisions Explained

**Why `thirdweb` (v5) instead of `@thirdweb-dev/react` (v4)?**
The v4 packages are deprecated as of June 2025. The v5 SDK uses a single `thirdweb` package with sub-path imports (`thirdweb/react`, `thirdweb/wallets`), is tree-shakeable, and supports the same `ConnectButton` and `inAppWallet` APIs.

**Why `PaymentElement` + `ExpressCheckoutElement` instead of Stripe Checkout (redirect)?**
The requirement specifies a popup overlay sitting on top of blurred content, exactly like NYT/WashPost. Stripe Checkout redirects to a hosted page, which breaks this UX. `PaymentElement` renders inline, and `ExpressCheckoutElement` provides the Apple Pay / Google Pay buttons (Stripe explicitly states wallet payments should use `ExpressCheckoutElement` to avoid duplication with `PaymentElement`).

**Why are providers scoped to specific pages, not the root layout?**
Both the Stripe Elements SDK and the ThirdWeb SDK load significant JavaScript. Wrapping them at the root layout would penalize every page (home listing, studio, etc.) with unnecessary bundle weight. Instead, only the `/demo` page and individual premium post pages mount the providers.

**Why separate Mock components instead of conditional rendering inside the real components?**
Clean separation of concerns. The mock components have zero dependency on external SDKs -- they are pure HTML/CSS. This means: (a) the demo page renders instantly without any SDK initialization, (b) there is no risk of runtime errors from uninitialized Stripe/ThirdWeb contexts, and (c) mock and real components can be styled independently.

**Why is the Sanity Studio embedded at `/studio` instead of deployed separately?**
The requirement says "embedded at /studio or configured separately." Embedding keeps the demo self-contained: a single `npm run dev` command gives you the blog, the demo page, and the content management studio. The catch-all route `[[...tool]]` handles all Studio sub-routes. Route groups `(blog)` ensure the Studio layout (which is full-viewport, no header) does not conflict with the blog layout.

**Graceful degradation strategy:**
Every external service integration follows the same pattern: (1) check for env var at module level, (2) export an `isXConfigured()` function, (3) provider wrappers pass through when unconfigured, (4) UI components swap to mock variants. The demo page at `/demo` always works because it uses hardcoded content and falls back to mock payment/auth UI.

