          Subscribe to continue reading
        </h2>
        <p className="font-body text-gray-600 text-center mb-6">
          Get unlimited access to premium articles for $9.99/month
        </p>

        {/* ThirdWeb social sign-in */}
        <div className="mb-6">
          <p className="text-sm text-gray-500 text-center mb-3">
            Already a member? Sign in
          </p>
          <div className="flex justify-center">
            <ThirdWebAuth />
          </div>
        </div>

        <div className="border-t border-gray-200 my-6" />

        {/* Stripe payment */}
        {isStripeConfigured() ? <StripeCheckout /> : <MockStripeCheckout />}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Key styling decisions:
- `font-title` class uses Futura (configured in Tailwind).
- `font-body` class uses Helvetica.
- The gradient goes from fully opaque white at the bottom to transparent at the top, so the article text fades out naturally.
- The card is `max-w-lg`, centered, with rounded corners and shadow -- matching modern paywall aesthetics.

---

### Phase 6: Blog Components

**Step 6.1 -- BlogPost: `src/app/components/blog/BlogPost.tsx`**

Renders a full blog post: title (Futura), author badge, published date, featured image, and body content (via `@portabletext/react`). Accepts a `isPremium` prop; when true, the component co-renders the `PaywallOverlay`.

Layout pattern:
```tsx
<article className="relative">
  <header>
    <h1 className="font-title text-4xl font-bold">{title}</h1>
    <AuthorBadge author={author} date={publishedAt} />
    {featuredImage && <img ... />}
  </header>
  <div className={isPremium ? 'max-h-[600px] overflow-hidden' : ''}>
    <PortableText value={body} />
  </div>
  {isPremium && <PaywallOverlay />}
</article>
```

The `max-h-[600px] overflow-hidden` truncates the article body so only the first portion is visible, reinforcing the paywall effect.

**Step 6.2 -- BlogPostCard: `src/app/components/blog/BlogPostCard.tsx`**

A card component for the listing page. Shows featured image, title, excerpt, author, and a "Premium" badge when `isPremium` is true.

**Step 6.3 -- AuthorBadge: `src/app/components/blog/AuthorBadge.tsx`**

Small component: author avatar (circular), name, and formatted date.

---

### Phase 7: The Demo Page

**Step 7.1 -- Constants file: `src/app/lib/constants.ts`**

Contains hardcoded demo content so the `/demo` page works without any external services:

```ts
export const DEMO_POST = {
  title: 'The Future of Decentralized Media',
  author: { name: 'Jane Nakamoto', avatar: null },
  publishedAt: '2025-01-15T10:00:00Z',
  isPremium: true,
  excerpt: 'How blockchain technology is reshaping content monetization...',
  body: [
    // 6-8 paragraphs of placeholder text (NOT lorem ipsum -- actual
    // readable placeholder about decentralized media, Web3, creator
    // economies, etc.)
  ],
};
```

**Step 7.2 -- Demo page: `src/app/demo/page.tsx`**

This is a self-contained page that renders the full paywall experience using hardcoded data. It does NOT depend on Sanity, Stripe, or ThirdWeb being configured. It imports mock components as fallbacks.

```tsx
import { DEMO_POST } from '@/app/lib/constants';
import { BlogPost } from '@/app/components/blog/BlogPost';
import { ThirdWebProviderWrapper } from '@/app/components/providers/ThirdWebProvider';
import { StripeProvider } from '@/app/components/providers/StripeProvider';

export const metadata = {
  title: 'Paywall Demo',
  description: 'Interactive demo of the paywalled blog experience',
};

export default function DemoPage() {
  return (
    <ThirdWebProviderWrapper>
      <StripeProvider>
        <main className="min-h-screen bg-white">
          <div className="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
            <BlogPost
              title={DEMO_POST.title}
              author={DEMO_POST.author}
              publishedAt={DEMO_POST.publishedAt}
              isPremium={DEMO_POST.isPremium}
              body={DEMO_POST.body}
              excerpt={DEMO_POST.excerpt}
              featuredImage={null}
            />
          </div>
        </main>
      </StripeProvider>
    </ThirdWebProviderWrapper>
  );
}
```

The provider wrappers detect missing env vars and pass through without wrapping, so the mock UI components render in their place. The page is always visually complete.

---

### Phase 8: Dynamic Blog Pages (Sanity-powered)

**Step 8.1 -- Home page: `src/app/page.tsx`**

An async Server Component that fetches posts from Sanity using `POSTS_QUERY`. Wraps the fetch in a try/catch; on failure (Sanity not configured), falls back to showing the demo post card with a link to `/demo`.

**Step 8.2 -- Post detail page: `src/app/(blog)/posts/[slug]/page.tsx`**

An async Server Component that fetches a single post by slug using `POST_BY_SLUG_QUERY`. If the post has `isPremium: true`, it wraps the page in the providers and renders `BlogPost` with the `PaywallOverlay`. If Sanity fetch fails, redirects to `/demo`.

---

### Phase 9: Root Layout and Providers

**Step 9.1 -- Root layout: `src/app/layout.tsx`**

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next';
import './globals.css';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'Paywalled Blog',
  description: 'A demo paywalled blog with Sanity CMS, Stripe, and ThirdWeb',
};

export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <body className="font-body antialiased text-gray-900">
        <header className="border-b border-gray-200 py-4 px-6">
          <nav className="max-w-5xl mx-auto flex items-center justify-between">
            <a href="/" className="font-title text-xl font-bold">
              The Paywall Times
            </a>
            <div className="flex items-center gap-4">
              <a href="/demo" className="text-sm text-gray-600 hover:text-black">
                Demo
              </a>
              <a href="/studio" className="text-sm text-gray-600 hover:text-black">
                Studio
              </a>
            </div>
          </nav>
        </header>
        {children}
      </body>
    </html>
  );
}
```

Providers (ThirdWeb, Stripe) are NOT in the root layout. They are only mounted on pages that need them (demo, individual premium posts) to avoid unnecessary SDK loading.

---

### Phase 10: TypeScript Types

**Step 10.1 -- `types/index.ts`**

```ts
export interface Author {
  name: string;
  slug?: { current: string };
  avatar?: any; // Sanity image reference
  bio?: string;
}

export interface Post {
  _id?: string;
  title: string;
  slug?: { current: string };
  excerpt?: string;
  featuredImage?: any;
  author?: Author;
  publishedAt?: string;
  isPremium: boolean;
  body?: any[]; // Portable Text blocks
}
```

---

## 4. Key Design Decisions Explained

**Why `thirdweb` (v5) instead of `@thirdweb-dev/react` (v4)?**
The v4 packages are deprecated as of June 2025. The v5 SDK uses a single `thirdweb` package with sub-path imports (`thirdweb/react`, `thirdweb/wallets`), is tree-shakeable, and supports the same `ConnectButton` and `inAppWallet` APIs.

**Why `PaymentElement` + `ExpressCheckoutElement` instead of Stripe Checkout (redirect)?**
The requirement specifies a popup overlay sitting on top of blurred content, exactly like NYT/WashPost. Stripe Checkout redirects to a hosted page, which breaks this UX. `PaymentElement` renders inline, and `ExpressCheckoutElement` provides the Apple Pay / Google Pay buttons (Stripe explicitly states wallet payments should use `ExpressCheckoutElement` to avoid duplication with `PaymentElement`).

**Why are providers scoped to specific pages, not the root layout?**
Both the Stripe Elements SDK and the ThirdWeb SDK load significant JavaScript. Wrapping them at the root layout would penalize every page (home listing, studio, etc.) with unnecessary bundle weight. Instead, only the `/demo` page and individual premium post pages mount the providers.

**Why separate Mock components instead of conditional rendering inside the real components?**
Clean separation of concerns. The mock components have zero dependency on external SDKs -- they are pure HTML/CSS. This means: (a) the demo page renders instantly without any SDK initialization, (b) there is no risk of runtime errors from uninitialized Stripe/ThirdWeb contexts, and (c) mock and real components can be styled independently.

**Why is the Sanity Studio embedded at `/studio` instead of deployed separately?**
The requirement says "embedded at /studio or configured separately." Embedding keeps the demo self-contained: a single `npm run dev` command gives you the blog, the demo page, and the content management studio. The catch-all route `[[...tool]]` handles all Studio sub-routes. Route groups `(blog)` ensure the Studio layout (which is full-viewport, no header) does not conflict with the blog layout.

**Graceful degradation strategy:**
Every external service integration follows the same pattern: (1) check for env var at module level, (2) export an `isXConfigured()` function, (3) provider wrappers pass through when unconfigured, (4) UI components swap to mock variants. The demo page at `/demo` always works because it uses hardcoded content and falls back to mock payment/auth UI.

---

## 5. Implementation Sequencing

The recommended order for building this:

1. **Scaffold** (Phase 1) -- 5 minutes. Get the Next.js project running with Tailwind.
2. **Types** (Phase 10) -- Define types first so everything downstream is typed.
3. **Constants** (Phase 7, Step 7.1) -- Hardcode demo content early; it unblocks UI work.
4. **UI components** (Phase 6 + Phase 5 mocks) -- Build `BlogPost`, `BlogPostCard`, `AuthorBadge`, `MockStripeCheckout`, `MockThirdWebAuth`, `PaywallOverlay`. At this point, the demo page can render with pure mock UI.
5. **Demo page** (Phase 7, Step 7.2) -- Wire up the demo page. Verify the visual paywall experience.
6. **Stripe integration** (Phase 3) -- Add the real Stripe provider, API route, and `StripeCheckout` component. Test with test keys.
7. **ThirdWeb integration** (Phase 4) -- Add the real ThirdWeb provider and `ThirdWebAuth`. Test with a ThirdWeb client ID.
8. **Sanity schemas and client** (Phase 2) -- Set up schemas, client, queries.
9. **Sanity Studio** (Phase 2, Step 2.8) -- Embed Studio at `/studio`.
10. **Dynamic blog pages** (Phase 8) -- Wire up home page and `[slug]` page to Sanity.
11. **Root layout and polish** (Phase 9) -- Final layout, navigation, responsive tweaks.

---

## 6. Potential Challenges and Mitigations

| Challenge | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| Futura is a commercial font; cannot be freely distributed | Ship with fallback stack (`Century Gothic`, `Trebuchet MS`). Include a README note about licensing. If Futura is available on the system, CSS will use it via `font-family`. |
| Apple Pay requires HTTPS and domain verification | Document this in README. For local dev, Apple Pay simply does not appear (Stripe handles this gracefully). The mock UI always shows the Apple Pay button for visual completeness. |
| `next-sanity`'s `NextStudio` may conflict with the blog layout | Use a route group `(blog)` for content pages and keep `/studio` outside it. The Studio page has no shared layout with blog pages. |
| ThirdWeb SDK requires a valid client ID for any wallet connection | The `MockThirdWebAuth` component provides a visual substitute. The real `ConnectButton` only mounts when `NEXT_PUBLIC_THIRDWEB_CLIENT_ID` is present. |
| Stripe `PaymentIntent` creation fails without `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY` | The API route returns 503. The `StripeProvider` detects missing config and renders children without `<Elements>`, which triggers the mock UI. |

---

### Critical Files for Implementation
- `/Users/josephgenest/Desktop/MercorSprint31926/model_b/src/app/components/paywall/PaywallOverlay.tsx` - Centerpiece of the entire project; orchestrates the blur overlay, Stripe checkout, and ThirdWeb auth into the NYT-style paywall experience
- `/Users/josephgenest/Desktop/MercorSprint31926/model_b/src/app/demo/page.tsx` - The self-contained demo page that must work without any env vars; wires together all providers and components with hardcoded content
- `/Users/josephgenest/Desktop/MercorSprint31926/model_b/sanity/schemas/post.ts` - Defines the post schema including the critical `isPremium` boolean toggle that drives paywall behavior
- `/Users/josephgenest/Desktop/MercorSprint31926/model_b/src/app/components/providers/StripeProvider.tsx` - Manages the Elements context with graceful fallback; controls whether real or mock Stripe UI renders
- `/Users/josephgenest/Desktop/MercorSprint31926/model_b/src/app/api/stripe/create-payment-intent/route.ts` - Server-side route that creates PaymentIntents with `automatic_payment_methods` enabled for Apple Pay/Google Pay support

